Overall, ChatGPT is a powerful tool for generating text responses and can be used in a variety of applications, such as chatbots and language translation.
However, ChatGPT is constantly improving and getting better at generating responses that sound more human-like.
ChatGPT is not a perfect representation of human language and can sometimes generate responses that are incorrect or don't make sense in the context of the conversation.
Because ChatGPT is a large language model, it has a vast amount of knowledge about language and is able to generate responses that sound natural and human-like.
The response generated by ChatGPT is not a pre-written response, but is generated on the fly based on the input it receives.
This means that when given a prompt, ChatGPT uses its knowledge of language and the patterns it has learned from vast amounts of text data to generate a response.
ChatGPT is a large language model trained by OpenAI to generate text based on a given prompt.

- Now, in the resulting matrix, we now have weighted embeddings.
- The weighted embeddings are ‚Äúcontextually influenced‚Äù and no longer depend only on the individual tokens.
- And this is how self-attention works! 11/

- weight matrix: 8x8
- original matrix: 8x512
- multiply the original matrix by weight. Resulting matrix: 8x512 (same as original) 
- Each embedding value is multiplied by the corresponding token‚Äôs weights 10/

- Now we use this matrix to give weights to the original embeddings. 
- For each token give high weights to the tokens it focuses more on.
- This weight matrix is obtained using row-wise softmax explained previously 9/

If we had 8 tokens, and each had an embedding size of 512,we will end up with an 8x8 matrix. After softmax, we have a matrix that tells us which token ‚Äúfocuses‚Äù on which other tokens. In other words, which token is contextually similar to other tokens in the context (sentence) 8/ https://t.co/RPC5RmRqmN

- Let‚Äôs call this matrix score matrix
- If we take row-wise softmax of this matrix, we will end up with another matrix in which all values are between 0 and 1 (for each row). 7/ https://t.co/tZgndIAaY8
If there are N tokens and we take the dot product of each token with itself and the rest of the tokens, we have an NxN matrix 6/ https://t.co/giJsm5sf5C

- Closer => dot product is large
- Far => dot product is small
- Is the word ‚Äúit‚Äù closer to ‚Äúproblem‚Äù or is it closer to ‚Äúxgboost‚Äù ? 5/ https://t.co/vNq3ba1098

- If we take dot product of the embedding for the word ‚Äúxgboost‚Äù with embeddings for all other words, we have this information.
- ‚Äúxgboost‚Äù will be closer to itself and some other words and far from the rest of the words. 4/ https://t.co/TdAuNzDyn5

- Which words are ‚Äúcloser‚Äù to the word ‚Äúxgboost‚Äù

Understanding self-attention. A Twitter thread üßµ
To understand what self-attention is and how it works, you need to know only the following terms:
- dot product
- matrix multiplication
- softmax
Note: it's not rocket science. let's keep it simple. 1/

I hope you liked this thread. If there are any mistakes in my implementation, please let me know and I can fix them :) 18/

And this is how inputs and outputs will look like. Here, batch size = 32, len of input seq = 128, len of output seq = 64. We add a linear + softmax to decoder output. This gives us a token prediction for each position (a classification problem) 17/ https://t.co/bZUyz00e2L

Now we have all the building blocks except positional encoding. Positional encoding tells the model an idea about where the tokens are located relative to each other. To implement positional encoding, we can simply use an embedding layer! 16/

Now we come to the special mask for targets, aka subsequent mask. The subsequent mask just tells the decoder not to look at tokens in the future. This is used in addition to the padding mask and is used only for training part. 15/ https://t.co/Cmay8SNLIk
Query comes from output of masked multi-head attention (after layernorm). Checkout the forward function and things are very easy to understand :) 14/ https://t.co/ckOgqlqtEl

The decoder layer consists of two different types of attention. the masked version has an extra mask in addition to padding mask. We will come to that. The normal multi-head attention takes key and value from final encoder output. key and value here are same. 13/ https://t.co/RvvX1uNzh4

Let's take a look at decoder now. The implementation is similar to that of the encoder except for the fact that each decoder also takes the final encoder's output as input. 12/ https://t.co/stL3KiPIXO
The mask just tells where not to look (e.g. padding tokens) 11/ https://t.co/oHYzejt180
Let's look at the forward function and the formula for self-attention (scaled). Ignoring the mask part, everything is pretty easy to implement. 10/ https://t.co/S4ByRoL19p

In the forward function, we apply the formula for self-attention. softmax(Q.K¬¥/ dim(k))V. torch.bmm does matrix multiplication of batches. dim(k) is the sqrt of k. Please note: q, k, v (inputs) are the same in the case of self-attention. 9/ https://t.co/Rlnyn6UTbV

self-attention in simple words is attention on the same sequence. I like to define it as a layer that tells you which token loves another token in the same sequence. for self-attention, the input is passed through 3 linear layers: query, key, value. 8/ https://t.co/Yib1sxqdBL

Now comes the fun part. Multi-head attention. We see it 3 times in the architecture. Multi-headed attention is nothing but many different self-attention layers. The outputs from these self-attentions are concatenated to form output the same shape as input. 6/ https://t.co/teOXtVGZnI

Let's take a look at the encoder layer. It consists of multi-headed attention, a feed forward network and two layer normalization layers. See forward(...) function to understand how skip-connection works. Its just adding original inputs to the outputs. 5/ https://t.co/CFMtQvAoK9

Similarly, we have the decoder composed of decoder layers. The decoder takes input from the last encoder layer and the target embeddings and target mask. enc_mask is the same as src_mask as explained previously 4/ https://t.co/l6TQFTqxyh

The encoder is composed of N encoder layers. Let's implement this as a black box too. The output of one encoder goes as input to the next encoder and so on. The source mask remains the same till the end 3/ https://t.co/FGSUrhNVtX

There are two parts: encoder and decoder. Encoder takes source embeddings and source mask as inputs and decoder takes target embeddings and target mask. Decoder inputs are shifted right. What does shifted right mean? Keep reading the thread. 2/ https://t.co/F8OpnbUDbG
